^BA should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: Full 128-character ASCII set. Native set: 0-9, A-Z, - . $ / + % and space. Control characters encoded via paired substitutes (& ' ( ) map to Ctrl $/%/+/). Two check digits (C and K) auto-calculated

constraints.message: ^BY should precede ^BB to set module width
^BB should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: Character set depends on mode. Mode A: Code 39 set (0-9, A-Z, - . $ / + % space); invalid chars produce no barcode or error. Mode E/F: full ASCII except ZPL-reserved chars; function codes via ^FH (FNC1=0x80, FNC2=0x81, FNC3=0x82, FNC4=0x83, NUL=0x84); chars above 0x84 invalid

constraints.message: ^BY should precede ^BC to set module width
^BC should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: Full ASCII via subsets A (control+upper), B (printable, default), C (numeric pairs 00-99). Subset switching via > codes (>9=start A, >:=start B, >;=start C, >5=C, >6=B, >7=A, >8=FNC1). Chars ^ > ~ require invocation codes. Mod 103 check digit always auto-calculated. Mode U: exactly 19 digits (auto-pads/truncates). Mode A: auto-selects subsets. Mode D: GS1 AI-aware, strips parens/spaces

constraints.message: ^BD should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: Mode 2/3: ^FD <hpm><lpm> with structured postal data. Mode 2 hpm: 15 numeric digits (class+country+zip5+zip4). Mode 3 hpm: 12 alphanumeric chars (class+country+postal6). lpm uses GS/RS/EOT separators (via ^FH for hex). Mode 4/5/6: accepts any data. UPS requires uppercase

^BE should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

^BF should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: Capacity: 250 7-bit ASCII chars, 150 8-bit chars, or 366 numeric digits; compact 2D variant of PDF417

fieldDataRules.notes: Code 39 character set (DoD application); lowercase letters auto-converted to uppercase; Mod 43 check digit mandatory and auto-generated

fieldDataRules.notes: Numeric only; max 14 digits when check digit e=B/C/D, max 13 when e=A (no check digit)

fieldDataRules.notes: Hexadecimal digits (0-9, A-F) per Plessey barcode standard; ZPL guide does not explicitly restrict character set but Plessey natively supports hex encoding

constraints.message: ^BQ should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: ^FD contains embedded switch fields: [D<codeNo><divs><parity>,]<errCorr><inputMode>,<[charMode]data>. Error correction (H/Q/M/L) and input mode (A=automatic, M=manual) are mandatory. Manual mode requires character mode: N=numeric (0-9), A=alphanumeric (0-9 A-Z space $%*+-./:), Bxxxx=byte (xxxx=4-digit count), K=Kanji. Automatic mode cannot encode bytes 0x80-0x9F and 0xE0-0xFF

constraints.message: ^BR requires ^BY to set module width defaults
^BR should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: Data format depends on symbology type (b param). Types 1-5 (DataBar variants): numeric 0-9, 14-digit GTIN, check digit auto-calculated. Type 6 (Expanded): alphanumeric GS1 AI element strings. Types 7-10 (UPC/EAN composites): numeric per underlying symbology. Types 11-12 (UCC/EAN-128 composites): full ASCII via Code 128 subsets

constraints.message: ^BY should precede ^BS to set module width
^BS should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: Exactly 2 or 5 numeric digits required; ZPL auto-pads on the left with zeros or truncates to required length. Used with ^BU (UPC-A) or ^B9 (UPC-E)

constraints.message: ^BT requires ^BY to set module width defaults
^BT should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: Comma-separated structured data: NNNNNN[,serial[,additional,...]]. Field 1 (ECI number): exactly 6 digits, required. Field 2 (serial): up to 25 alphanumeric chars (no punctuation), stored in MicroPDF417. Field 3+ (additional): up to 25 alphanumeric chars each. Total including commas must not exceed 150 bytes. If no comma after ECI, only Code 39 prints

constraints.message: ^BY should precede ^BU to set module width
^BU should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: 11 data digits; 12th check digit auto-calculated

constraints.message: ^BX should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)

fieldDataRules.notes: Quality 0-140: max 596 chars; character set by format ID (f): 1=numeric+space, 2=uppercase+space, 3=alphanumeric+punctuation, 4=alphanumeric+space, 5=full 7-bit ASCII, 6=full 8-bit ISO (default). Quality 200 (ECC 200): max 3072 bytes; escape sequences via ~ or _ (param g) for control chars and FNC codes

fieldDataRules.notes: Numeric digits only. Length depends on postal type (t param): Postnet (t=0): 5, 9, or 11 digits; Planet Code (t=1): 11 or 13 digits; USPS Intelligent Mail (t=3): 20, 25, 29, or 31 digits. Check digit auto-calculated where applicable

constraints.message: Takes immediate effect. All subsequent format commands must use the new prefix character. Use ^JUS to persist across power cycles.
Takes immediate effect. Use ^JUS to persist across power cycles.

Up to 256 source/destination remapping pairs can follow (s1,d1,s2,d2,...). Remapping is only valid when a = 0-13. The spec models only the first 3 parameters (a, s1, d1); additional pairs are accepted by the parser but not individually validated. Full variable-length pair validation is a known limitation.
Values 18-23, 25, and 32 are reserved.
Values 28-30 require firmware V60.14.x/V50.14.x or later.
Values 31, 33-36 require firmware V60.16.x or later.
Duplicate letter designators reset all assignments to defaults. Out-of-spec parameters cause the command to be ignored. Use ^JUS to persist across power cycles.
Print Mode Kiosk (^MMK) is required; outside kiosk mode this command has no effect. KR403 platform support.
Firmware X.12+ automatically expands character cache as needed, so this command is typically unnecessary on those versions.
KR403 printer support. Missing or invalid parameters cause the command to be ignored.
Takes immediate effect. All subsequent control commands must use the new prefix character. Use ^JUS to persist across power cycles.
A matching built-in font letter replaces that built-in font until power-off; a different letter adds an extra font. Assignment persists until power-off or reassignment.
^FB is meaningful with a following ^FD/^FV
^FB should precede its field data (^FD/^FV)
Without Real-Time Clock hardware this command is ignored. Include it in each label field command string whenever Real-Time Clock values are needed.
empty field data

Only applies to the immediately following ^FD field.
^FH should precede field data (^FD/^FV)
A font can have up to five fonts linked to it. Use ^JUS to permanently save. Linking remains until broken or printer power off.
Only works with ^B7 (PDF417) and ^BF (MicroPDF417) for structured append. Maximum 60 x,y pairs. Ignored with any other commands.

~HL is processed immediately; ^HL is processed after all previous formats. In firmware X.20.16Z and later, logging is disabled by default and ^HL clears the log and restarts recording; ~HL does not automatically clear the log.

commands.name: Return RFID Data Log to Host

constraints.message: Tag calibration can take up to 5 minutes. Load RFID media, calibrate printer, close printhead, and feed at least one label before running. Results are returned to the host computer.
Firmware V60.14.x, V50.14.x, or later required.

Returns a formatted ASCII string of object names to the host. Each object is listed on a fixed-length line starting with an asterisk. An optional f parameter (c=column, d=default) is supported in firmware V60.16.0Z and V53.16.0Z or later.
Extension of ^HG command. The image is uploaded in the form of a ~DY command with the data field always encoded in ZB64 format.

When info_type is 'o', an extended format is used: ^HZO,d:o.x,l where d = device (R:,E:,B:,A:), o = object name (1-16 chars), x = extension (.FNT,.GRF,.PNG,.ZPL,.DAT,.ZOB,.STO), and l = long filename support (Y/N, default N).
^IM should appear before its ^FS
^JM must be entered before the first ^FS command in a format. Effects are persistent. Using ^JMB causes UPS MaxiCode to become out of specification.
Applies to Xi4, RXi4, ZM400, ZM600, RZ400, or RZ600 printers with the external ZebraNet 10/100 print server using firmware v1.1.5 or later.
Without Real-Time Clock hardware, Display Mode is forced to 0 (Version Number). With Display Mode 0 and RTC hardware present, config label and control panel use format 1.
With no parameters, the printer name and description are set to blank strings. Use ^JUS to save settings.
Protected Mode blocks this command. In Protected Mode, use JSON-formatted Protect commands with SGD display.password.current.
KR403 printer required. Sets parameters for Kiosk mode (^MMK).
Must come before the first ^FS command for compatibility. Setting is retained until printer is turned off or a new ^LS command is sent.
Range varies by printer: HC100 0-120, XiIIIPlus 600dpi -240 to 240, all others -120 to 120. Value shown on front panel is double the ZPL value.

Firmware V60.15.x, V50.15.x, or later required. The type parameter must be specified as R or C for print, threshold, and frequency to be saved. The Early Warning Maintenance setting must be ON (via ^JH).
Must be used with ^FV to produce a label template.
Each ^MD command adjusts relative to the current darkness value. On XiIIIPlus/Xi4/RXi4, accepts values in increments of 0.1. On G-Series printers the value is persistent across power cycles.
Value S (short calibration) is only supported on Xi4, RXi4, XiIIIPlus, PAX, ZM400/ZM600, RZ400/RZ600, and S4M printers.
Firmware V60.15.x, V50.15.x, or later required. Printing of the message is controlled by ^MA. All characters following the comma and preceding the next ~ or ^ define the message string.
The maximum label length must be equal to or greater than the actual label length for calibration to work properly.
Available modes depend on printer model and installed options. Omitted or invalid parameters cause the command to be ignored.
Parameter b is only used when mode is set to M (mark sensing). Range varies: -80 to 283 (direct-thermal), -240 to 566 (600 dpi), -75 to 283 (KR403), -120 to 283 (all others).
A value must be entered or the command is ignored.
Each mode must be disabled with an individual ^MP command.
Should appear at the beginning of the label format.
Works field-by-field. To reset conversion, enter matching values for b and c.
When a parameter is not given, the instruction is ignored.
This command is ignored on Xi4, RXi4, ZM400, ZM600, RZ400, and RZ600 printers. A single print server can be installed in the S4M at a time.
Supported on Xi4, RXi4, ZM400/ZM600, RZ400/RZ600 printers which support simultaneous installation of internal, external, and wireless print servers.
The last network ID number set is the one recognized by the system. Used only with RS-485 printer communications.
Applies to parallel-port print servers only. While the printer is primary, any wired print server inserted will use the printer's settings.
For Xi4, RXi4, ZM400/ZM600, and RZ400/RZ600 printers, Zebra recommends using ^ND instead of ^NS.
Firmware V60.14.x, V50.14.x, or later required.

commands.name: Slew Given Number of Dot Rows

constraints.message: ~PH feeds one label after the format currently being printed is done or during printer pause. ^PH feeds one blank label after the current format prints.
KR403 printer required. See ~PL for present length addition.

~PP stops printing immediately after the current label completes. ^PP is not immediate  several labels might print before the pause takes effect. The printer remains paused until PAUSE is pressed or ~PS is sent.
Speed values are capped by the printer's maximum capability. Letter aliases: A=2, B=3, C=4, D=6, E=8 ips.
Partition sizes must add up to the total bit size (n). The largest individual partition size is 64 bits.
Omitted parameters inherit from the previous ^RB; all parameters persist for subsequent formats.
Use a field variable (^FN) to print tag data on the label or return data to the host.
Data for write operations is provided via ^FD.

Three distinct sub-formats: ^RLP (lock all, no params), ^RLB,s,n (lock sections), ^RLM,k,a,e,u (lock/unlock banks). The mode letter is concatenated directly to ^RL without a comma. For lock/unlock (M mode), the access password must be set to non-default (not 00000000).
Position tag data above the read/write position. Programming position applies to all labels until changed or tag calibration is run.

Printers automatically select the best antenna and power levels during RFID transponder calibration. For Japan, maximum RFID read and write power are limited to comply with local radio regulations; any power setting of 24 or higher results in the same output.
Missing, out-of-spec, unsupported parameters, or ZPL-override DIP switch settings cause this command to be ignored. Use ^JUS to persist changes through power-up.
Firmware V53.15.x or later required. Both parameters must be accepted values; otherwise the entire command is ignored.
^SL must be placed before the first ^FO command in the format.

Incrementing/decrementing occurs after all replicates for each serial number are printed (per ^PQ r parameter). On media-out recovery, the first reprinted label keeps the serial number from the partial label (controlled by ^JZ).
A single ^SO2 command is supported per label; use ^SO3 for additional offsets.
The clock_set value must be specified.
Can improve throughput on complex labels by allowing printing to begin before the entire label is formatted. Precise positioning requires trial and error. Drops any field that is out of order.
Setting a value higher than the printhead rating could damage the printhead. New printer models automatically set head resistance.
This command is ignored on the HC100 printer. Maximum values for parameters depend on printer platform.

commands.name: Set Date and Time (for Real-Time Clock)

constraints.message: Missing or invalid condition type or destination parameters cause this command to be ignored. Sub-options e and f depend on destination type.
Remains active until another ^SZ command is sent or printer power-off. Missing or invalid parameters cause this command to be ignored.
^TB should appear before its ^FS

^TB is the preferred command for printing fields or blocks of text instead of ^FB. Supports complex text layout features. Justification comes from ^FO, ^FT, or ^FN. Data between < and > is processed as escape sequences. Available in firmware V60.14.x, V50.14.x, or later.

Source and destination devices must be different and valid. At least one source parameter and one destination parameter are required. Zebra files (Z:*.*) cannot be transferred. Destination space exhaustion cancels the transfer.
Legacy: for firmware prior to V50.15.x or X60.15.x. Use ^WX for newer firmware. Not valid for Link-OS v6 or later. Be careful to include the exact number of commas during encryption key setup.
Legacy: for firmware prior to V50.15.x or X60.15.x. For newer firmware, use ^WX to set the security type and related parameters.

This command does not apply to the S4M. With a wireless password set, MAC Address, ESSID, WLAN Security, WEP Type, WEP Index, and Reset Network will not appear on the control panel until the wireless password is entered.
This command is not valid for Link-OS printers and is only supported in selected other models. Used for 802.11b wireless print servers.

Supporting parameters vary by security type. Values 2, 3 for security type and parameters b, c, d, e, f, g, h are ignored for Link-OS 6.0 or later. For certificate files, the time on the printer must be set correctly. The ^WX command replaces individual ZPL commands for different security types.

Because no forward feed occurs, backfeed before printing the next label is not necessary, improving throughput. The last label in a batch should not contain this command. In cutter mode, ^XB suppresses both backfeed and cutting to prevent jamming.
^XG should appear before its ^FS
Responds to mobile printers only. Returns <STX>hh.hh,bb.bb,bt<ETX><CR><LF> where hh.hh = head voltage, bb.bb = battery voltage, bt = battery temperature in Celsius.
Response starts with STX, CR LF inserted between each line, and ends with ETX. Must be an accepted value or the command is ignored.

Returns three data strings to the host. String 1: communication settings, paper out, pause, label length, buffer status, diagnostics mode, corrupt RAM, temperature. String 2: function settings, head up, ribbon out, thermal transfer mode, print mode, label waiting, labels remaining, graphics count. String 3: password and static RAM status. Does not respond during MEDIA OUT, RIBBON OUT, HEAD OPEN, REWINDER FULL, or HEAD OVER-TEMPERATURE.
Without ^SX alerts configured, the printer will not respond to this command.

Sending a print format or pressing a control-panel key exits Discharge Mode. A connected charger triggers automatic recharge after discharge completes. Green power LED flashes in groups of three during discharge.
Use at the beginning of any label format to specify which printer on the network is to be used. The commands ^MW, ~NC, ^NI, ~NR, and ~NT require RS-422/485 printer communications.
KR403 printer required. Total eject during ^PN = 50 mm + ~PL value + ^PN value.
Only accepted via USB for security. Sent over Bluetooth, Ethernet, or other channels: command is ignored. Causes the printer to exit Protected Mode. Flash wipe takes considerable time.
Values C and R require Xi4, RXi4, ZM400/ZM600, RZ400/RZ600, S4M, or G-Series printers.
A value must be specified or the command is ignored.
The ^MD command value is added to the ~SD value.
On XiIIIPlus/Xi4/RXi4, the darkness range is 0 to 30 in 0.1 increments.
Parameter missing or invalid: command is ignored.
For 600 dpi printers, the step size doubles. With fewer than 3 characters, the command is ignored.
